  "doc_id": "31175",
  "text": "The effectiveness of central actors (here, the network manager, operational staff and clinical geneticists) as knowledge brokers is usually a combination of both their expertise and their accessibility [CITATION_1] . We did not explore here whether these central actors are nominated because they are available, or because they have the sought after expertise, or because they are likely to be able to direct enquiries to the appropriate person (acting as a broker). As seen in other networks [CITATION_2] , there are risks here for a key player to be overloaded with requests, or to leave the network, leading to the potential for network fragmentation or for a regression of actor behaviour back into silos, or for a slowing down of collaborative working [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Mitigation strategies include sharing the particular role they are enacting (brokerage or source of expertise) across other members, or diffusing responsibilities across the network. For routine requests that the network manager might field, making information available via electronic means may also be considered.",
